    юддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддддды

               Partial symbol matching and selection from a list, so
               that very long names can be uniquely identified.

               Uparrow and Downarrow will retrieve previously
               entered names.

               Internal tracing was added to DEBUG.286, EWTCONT.286
               and EWTTERM.286 to help diagnose problems quickly.

    P0008084 - Fixed a problem with "get address error".

               When stepping into a function and line numbers are not
               present, a message is given.

               LCV files that contain more than 10,000 lines are not
               displayed correctly.  It was fixed.

               A symbol is not found if it is in a file that is linked
               in a sequence after any assembler OBJ file.  It was fixed.

               CONST data causes a "get address error" message.  It was
               fixed.

               Popup windows are sometimes not completely removed.  It
               was fixed.

               PV errors can occur while stepping into a function, or
               single stepping.  This fix is in the 4690 OS kernel,
               V3R1 with appropriate fixes, or a later release.

               Placing certain BASIC arrays or strings in the storage
               window can cause a dump.  It was fixed.

               A message and reverse coloration marks source lines of
               an LCV file that do not appear to match the line numbers
               for them in the CDV file.

    P8084.B  - Support was added for Data Breakpoints <CTRL>-F4.  A 4690
               OS kernel fix is also required, at V3R2 or a later
               release, or V3R1 with appropriate patches.

               Support was added for keystroke recording and playback
               (DEBUG.KBR, DEBUG.KBP).

               In the Storage Window, only one line was shown for arrays
               and for strings longer than 16 bytes.  It was fixed.

               <CNTRL>-Break now works to stop a running application.
               A 4690 OS kernel fix is also required, at V3R2 or a later
               release.

               A turquoise screen flicker occurs at the top of the
               screen if the storage window is empty.  It was fixed.

               Dumped while single stepping on an ASM screen under
               unusual data conditions.

               INIT38: message was changed to provide more diagnostic
               information.

    P8084.C  - Display Memory now provides eight lines of sixteen bytes
               in the storage window, rather than just one line.

               At any time when in a Source window, and especially after
               pressing <CTRL>-Break, you can press <ALT>-F7 to show
               the screen that was displayed prior to pressing RUN (F2,
               F5 or F6) or selecting pulldown Search - Function.
               Repeatedly pressing <ALT>-F7 will show the source screens
               that existed prior to that point.

               DEBUGCDV was changed so that the /B switch is the
               default.  This uses selectors rather than segments, and
               allows applications over 1 MB in size.  To return to
               prior behavior, use the /L switch.

               If your application does not start, the RC is now shown.
               If the RC is xxxx4188, "SRTL" is also indicated.

               If you are missing User Logical File Names for DEBUG: or
               HELP:, the debugger will not start correctly.  It now
               checks for these two defines, and prints a message and
               terminates if either is missing.

               INIT32, INIT36 and INIT38: messages were changed to
               provide more diagnostic information.

               The "-" character was added to the list of delimiters so
               that symbol names in BASIC and C will be correctly found
               if a subtraction operator immediately follows the name.

               /O4 flag generates DEBUG.SCR file for use in capturing
               debugger screens.

               Displaying integers in the storage window shows both the
               integer and the hex value.

               DBINFO was changed to recognize CDV files that were
               built from postlinked 286 files.  It was further changed
               to accept either the FILE or the FILE.CDV form of its
               input file.

    P8084.D  - The storage window can now be expanded beyond the
               original limit of 10 lines.

               Partial name matching now ignores type checking for data
               variables to improve performance.

               A popup window now informs you if you have used the /M
               switch inappropriately.

               A popup window now informs you of a possible LCV/OBJ
               file mismatch on the first detected mismatch on each
               LCV file that is displayed.

               The data breakpoint reporting was changed to scroll up
               by two lines from the trap location so that the
               offending instruction is more likely to be displayed in
               the current window.

               You can press <CTRL>-F7 to show the statement that calls
               the current function.

               Support was added to display the CBASIC function call
               history.  You must link the latest SB286LT.L86 with your
               application in order to capture this trace for display.
               You can go directly to the display of the source code for
               any of the functions in this display by moving the
               highlight to that line and pressing Enter.

               The debugger now exchanges release level information with
               EWTCONT.286 and EWTTERM.286 when your application is
               loaded to ensure that those parts of the debugger are
               compatible with each other.

               DEBUGCDV provides two workarounds for processing of
               programs that have more than 64KB of global symbol
               information.

               The file names and numbers can be displayed for all
               CBASIC open sessions.

               The last fifteen CBASIC runtime errors can be displayed.

               While stepping through an ON ERROR routine, the ERR, ERRN
               and ERRF values are shown at the bottom of the screen.

               An error message is written to DEBUGLOG and to the screen
               if you are trying to load a terminal application using a
               path name that is too long.

               Support is provided for debugging Terminal applications in
               the Terminal Session Server environment.

               EWTTERM2.286 provides status messages to the 2x20 display.
               If you have a 2x20, copy EWTTERM2.286 to EWTTERM.286.  If
               your 2x20 is redirected, do not use or copy EWTTERM2.286,
               because it will hang on its open of ADXPIA.

               Breakpoints which follow a CALL statement disappeared when
               you single step over the CALL.  It was fixed.

               The /o8 switch prevents the showing of error or trace
               messages on the screen. They are written to DEBUGLOG only.

               LCV files can now be refreshed during a debugger run.  Use
               Ctrl-Home / Ctrl-End to flush the in-memory buffers.

               The debugger now looks for the source LCV file again when
               you press Window - sOurce from an assembler screen.
               Previously, you had to exit the debugger and then restart
               it.

               The debugger preserves the contents of its keyboard recall
               buffer by saving it in file DEBUG.KRB when it ends, and
               reloading it when it is restarted.

               You can set conditions and stopping values for data
               breakpoints so that the debugger continues to run when
               breakpoint variables are set to values that are not of
               interest to you.

               You can go to the display of the source for the current
               CBASIC ON ERROR routine by pressing Display - oN error.

               You can go to the display of the source for a called
               function by placing the cursor on its name in a source
               window and pressing "=".

